<BlogPost
  title="4 Ways to Build Healthy Habits in Kids"
  description="The start of the year is a great time to build lasting wellness routines for your children. Here are four evidence-based strategies."
  publishDate="2024-02-03"
  category="Family Health"
>

The new year is a great time to reflect on the habits we want to build — especially for the youngest members of our families. As a community pharmacy serving families across Stafford, Sugar Land, and Missouri City, TX, we often get asked how to set kids up for a lifetime of good health.

Here are four strategies that work.

## 1. Make Movement a Family Activity

Kids who see their parents exercise are far more likely to be active themselves. You don't need a gym membership — a walk after dinner, a weekend bike ride, or even dancing in the living room counts.

The goal is consistency and fun. Aim for 60 minutes of movement per day for school-age children, and make it social whenever possible.

## 2. Build a Sleep Routine

Sleep is one of the most undervalued aspects of children's health. Poor sleep affects mood, focus, immune function, and even appetite regulation.

Consistent bedtimes — even on weekends — are more effective than the total number of hours alone. Start winding down 30–60 minutes before bed: dim the lights, put away screens, and try quiet activities like reading.

## 3. Make Medication Adherence Easy

If your child takes a daily medication, adherence matters. Missing doses — even occasionally — can affect how well a treatment works.

Ask your pharmacist about:
- **Multi-dose packaging** — pre-sorted daily doses
- **Medication synchronization** — one monthly fill date for all family prescriptions
- **Flavor options** — many liquid medications can be flavored at the pharmacy

At TRS Pharmacy, we're happy to work with you to make your child's medication routine as simple as possible.

## 4. Model Healthy Eating (Without Perfection)

Research consistently shows that children eat what they see adults eat. The goal isn't perfection — it's exposure and normalization.

Keep fruits and vegetables visible and accessible. Cook together when you can. Avoid using food as a reward or punishment, which can create unhealthy emotional associations.

